<idx:iform value="båtu" exact="yes" />
</idx:infl>
</idx:orth>
<p>Type of game. The equipment consists of a round stick for to six inches long, one to one and a half inches in diameter, a flat on both ends, discs made of stone or metal, approximately three inches in diamter. Players stand ten or mor feet away from the stick, which has been placed on end, and take turns thrying to knock down the stick with their discs. Whoever knocks down the stick is declared the winner.</p>

<idx:short><a id="4243"></a>
<idx:orth value="in"><b>in</b>
<idx:iform value="in" exact="yes" />
</idx:infl>
</idx:orth>
<p>1. Adjectivizing infix--used to form modifires from nominals, similar to English -ish. Guaka "cow", guinaka "cowish". Å'påka' "white", ina'påka' "whitish". Kåhet "orange", kinahet "orangish". 2. Nominalizing infix. Li'e' "to see", lini'e'-ña "The thing he saw." Nå'I "to give", nina'I "gift (thing that is given)." 3. Goal focus infix. </p>
</idx:short>

<idx:iform value="sikat" exact="yes" />
</idx:infl>
</idx:orth>
<p>1. Creep; stalk; still-hunt; move furtively or slinkingly; sneak; steal (so as to be unobserved). 2. Nod; nodding; act of nodding; make a downward motion of the head involutarily because of drowsiness. 3. Preparing cocks to fight int eh arena. The cocks are held, allowed to peck at eachother, then are placed on the ground and held by the tail feathers while they begin to scratch, rais the neck feathers and bob their heads up and down.</p>
